{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489407"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:15:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:15:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"651"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/651"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.62,0.05,0.18,0.03,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"651"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"17642"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/651"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"651"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"8710"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1144"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"676"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1759"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2222"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"17642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/17642"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 77-year-old man presents with a two month history of progressive vocal hoarseness and difficulty swallowing (worse with liquids). His surgical history includes a left total hip arthroplasty, as well as recent inferior turbinate  and endoscopic sinus surgery for  longstanding chronic sinusitis and nasal congestion. His medical conditions include COPD, obesity, hyperlipidaemia and chronic back pain. He is a long-term smoker, with a 60 pack-year history. He believes his COPD has been much worse of late. Physical examination is unremarkable, with a normal neck exam. Flexible nasal endoscopy shows a left vocal cord palsy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to order?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT head and chest","Thyroid ultrasound","Barium swallow","PET scan","Endoscopy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an extensive smoking history, which is a significant risk factor for carcinoma of the lung. In combination with the recent worsening of COPD symptoms (likely manifesting as shortness of breath and reduced exercise tolerance), this patient most likely has lung cancer. In this case, there has almost certainly been malignant infiltration of the left recurrent laryngeal nerve (a branch of CN X), which supplies innervation to all of the intrinsic muscles of the larynx, except for the cricothyroid muscles, as well as sensation to the larynx below the level of the vocal cords. Unilateral injury to the recurrent laryngeal nerve will mainly present with vocal hoarseness. Swallowing difficulties are also encountered on occasion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the head and chest\u003C/strong\u003E will be useful in identifying the presence of a lung cancer, as well as any metastatic spread (fairly likely in this case). This is helpful for staging, prognostication and evaluation of surgical treatment options. As such, this is the correct answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroid ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be useful, as recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy most often occurs in the context of thyroid or parathyroid surgery. Whilst thyroid cancer can be associated with infiltration of the recurrent laryngeal nerve, this patients displays no symptoms or signs of thyroid cancer (i.e. no neck lump). As such, thyroid ultrasound is an incorrect answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebarium swallow\u003C/strong\u003E might be indicated if there was a suggestion of an oseophageal motility disorder (e.g. achalasia). There is no evidence of this and given that fact, barium swallow is an incorrect answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EPET scan\u003C/strong\u003E is not a suitable first-line investigation in the work-up of suspected lung cancer, however may be performed at a later stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if the problem was thought to be a primarily oesophageal in nature. For example, had this patient presented with weight loss and progressive difficulties in swallowing (worse with solids than liquids), an endoscopy may be warranted to investigate a possible oesophageal cancer. Oesophageal cancer can cause recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy, however given this patient\u0027s extensive smoking history and the nature of his presentation, lung cancer is more likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hoarseness and a long smoking history must always raise the possibility of underlying malignancy."],"references":["Nasim F, Sabath BF,  Eapen GA. Lung Cancer. Med Clin N Am 2019; 103:463\u201373"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"8710"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"651"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"8710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/8710"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2021-10-08T07:24:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2021-10-08T07:24:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"651"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"17642"}}},"meta":{"canDelete